The paper deals with lower bounds on the query complexity of determining correlated equilibrium in n-player games. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of algorithms and computational complexity, which could place it in the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. The query model used in the paper also involves the use of black boxes, which could suggest that the paper belongs to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper involves the computation of correlated equilibrium, which could place it in the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of information theory to establish lower bounds, which could suggest that it belongs to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
